sonius, Claudian, and Prudentius we can see the increasing importance of distinctions between old and new, ancient and modern, forgotten and remembered. The strange traditionalism and verbalism of the day often concealed a desire for immediacy and presence. We can see these changes most clearly in the expectations placed upon readers. The space that remains is the space that the reader comes to inhabit, as would increasingly become the case in the literature of the Latin Middle Ages.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAuthors and readerszRome. 0aLatin poetryxAppreciation. 0aLatin poetryxHistory and criticism. 0aReader-response criticism. 4aAncient History & Classical Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPoetry & Criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  alatin literature, Ausonius, Claudian, Prudentius,.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145500140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801455001423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801455001/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles